## 🤔 What If Your Network Uses a Different Subnet?

Some home networks use:
- `192.168.0.0/24` (different second octet)
- `192.168.1.0/24` (most common)
- `10.0.0.0/24` (sometimes routers/ISPs)
- `172.16.x.x` to `172.31.x.x` (less common at home)

**To check your actual subnet:**

```bash
ip addr show | grep "inet " | grep -v 127.0.0.1
```

Look for output like:
```
inet 192.168.1.42/24 brd 192.168.1.255 scope global dynamic noprefixroute wlp3s0
                ^^^
                This /24 means subnet 192.168.1.0/24
```

**If your IP is `192.168.0.42`** → use `192.168.0.0/24` instead of `192.168.1.0/24`:
```bash
sudo ufw allow from 192.168.0.0/24 to any port 5173 proto tcp
```

**If your IP is `10.0.1.42`** → use `10.0.0.0/24` (or wider `10.0.0.0/8` for any 10.x network):
```bash
sudo ufw allow from 10.0.0.0/24 to any port 5173 proto tcp
```

