## 💡 Future Considerations

### When you add more dev servers
Each new tool (Vite, Storybook, backend API, etc.) usually picks an unused port. Just add a rule for each:
```bash
sudo ufw allow from 192.168.1.0/24 to any port 3000 proto tcp   # Next.js, etc.
sudo ufw allow from 192.168.1.0/24 to any port 8080 proto tcp   # Common API port
```

### For production
None of this matters — Cloudflare Pages handles HTTPS, edge servers, DDoS protection, etc. UFW is just for local dev safety.

### For travel / coffee shops
On untrusted networks (airport WiFi, etc.), even `192.168.1.0/24` could be shared with strangers. In those cases:
- Disable UFW rule temporarily: `sudo ufw delete <rule-number>`
- Or use Vite's `--host localhost` (which we have by default when not using `--host`)

